Brussel m. Antoni Russeau

Londoen mr JBany Maijnand
C 21 mank
on the 17. curtt. remitted you £135„4.1 sch on Edward Brownes att sicht, which I hope is come
safe to hands, now shall answer yd of 27 past, as for spanish cloathes, I hope you will match
the rest in ordered according to dircetions, besides them pleases to provide one bale more as many
of the kayes as you can finde fitt the patt., & the rest as best you shall iudge
I hope the pack whites be ready to be shipt, of each sent 10. viz of the EE yallow & WW
red mark, though 5 of each will serve my turne a while. the last WW. red marchy you
send mee in the bale M„N.1 were worse by 4p. then them of last yare, neither had
they the usuall mark, so pray be carefull in buying, for I finde that our best proffitt
depends of the will buying in. I hope the G.N. silver mary ships, which I should be gladd
to understand. for the future pleases to wrapp my packes with bayes, or cottens as best
you can finde pennyworths yett for a try all would have the bale, of spanish cloathes to be
wrapped with 2 cloathes. which de mont did alwayes, & to goot as well from the north
as london, well 200 cloathes yarly, without any charges on them, butt you must take such
cullours as will not spott by the wett. I could wish to see yd northres goods here, before
you should go to the north for to gov. my self accordingly, butt the latter end of may will
be to late I doubt to have kersies, bayes & ilwathes here in the latter end of june, or
beginning of July, as to do well, itt must be. as for the bustynes of Peeters I hope ended
before now, that with remitting what is resting, I may be red of that concerne also
returne you thancks that you will take care for the desined ale, which I exspect accordingly
yet bills on me are accepted, & shall be duely discharged, with more remises first
I have given you credit for the goods aboard clarck & Pindan, I nept please to advise
mee if Pindar shall soone depart as also what further pattes in our concernes
att the end of this month you shall have acc of sale
Pray a word if there be no now mode with you, here there are come a sort of clouded
cullours, if you have any, send mee pat. & amonghst them now inordered e
I doubt m. Scawen wants the cottons, make. 9 demy p on 8 to each bale & 2 bales, butt
take good care that not above in one bale
Lyen r. Wille Sealy
C 21 march 1682 antw
mij last to you was on the 14 curtt. to which referre you onely that what I wanted to compleat
the parcell of new seeds hath cost 4 stivers att, so that itt is yett resen, & could not now compleat
another such parcell for ½ a pound more, I found old seed for 2 barnels more, so that there
is5 of new, & 7 of old, bought & sent to Bruges, which I exspect will, prove to content, coming
butt out of the countrey have no time to send you the acctt which p rept you may exspect, so
then this serves pertely in answer to yc of 28th past, where by yd order for the old seed in larger
then the formar, so that if por. I shall gett some more old seed, in case I can gett itt ready for
Ewings, the old I bought lost, is butt of 1680 & endeed many will hardely distinguish itt, or know
itt of the new & is made up bey itt self in N. 11 & 12, butt will cost 2¾ at for drawing
the value I'll do itt to yd most advantidge when I have all the charges payd as well at Gant
as shipping att Bruges, so make itt butt one bustijnes you desire to know what a binlander
of 16 a 20 ton will cost traight to come for Topsham or London, & there to be discharged, or to
returnes, back for yd. actt. for Binlanders of 16 a 20 ton there is non, butt well of 16 a 20 last
which is as much againe, as here there is one Cristian de wever, which is a brave seaman
& hath zealands zeabr (because of the quarrell betwipt spaine & bBrandenbourgh) & nm. of
George Great 20 last or 40 ton, & arkes from hence or Bruges to Topsham £60
or from hence to Londen £50- for going & coming on either of thes places, if I can serve
you m'any thingh, knowing yd bustijnes I doubt not, butt shall be able to give you good
content in all, wel have ex. here for all places of Europe, & if you advise mee what
thread you want, shall answer you the needfull, the other com you mention will not
in corridge now here to sell
Londen m. William Scawen
I have before mee yd of 3 cur. in which I am sorry to see the opinion you have of mee
truly I doubt finde trade now so, that any one here can make haste to be rich, butt
hath enough to do to gett living & then neither will any gaine prosper, except itt be iustly
gotten, pray s lett mee not come to any degree of that nature in yd preiudice, for I should
be hartely sonry for itt, so lett mee rectefie, what you finde in mee an erreur. if a trade
doth not suceed to exspectation, there in wee must have pat. & bare itt equally. I am
att Peeter Willart that brought over the Tnfortunate callicoes, & blame him for haveing
opened one or 2 bales, where by they disconvered, so I hope I shall make him pay
something to, to help our loss, which if succeds shall be added for yd. share to the ƒ860-
mentiones, & to be generous have given yd acctt curts credit for ƒ 870- is £145- flemish
for the valew of which & £22- 11en due to you & ballance shall send a brave pack of
tykes according to yd. dixcetion. I take notice you have bought some goods for mee
I could wish you had not putt to be dyed all the browne salempores, butt send some with
the whites hether, m. Maynard will gett ready 2 bales of cottons of 8 a 9 demy
each, in them you may fould the blew salempores, & the white with what romales
you shall buy for mee, & some dyed salempores the long cloth & the rest of the salempores
dyed to come dixcetely m'a bales or 2, butt observe that in the cottons be not foalded above
40ƒ in a bale except the romales which take no roome please to dispatch the goods
when you can convenientley & give an acctt. of all. yd bill I have accepted
